The AF2011 double barrel pistol comes as the very first industrial double barrel semi-automatic pistol ever made.

The AF-2011 comes with adjustable rear sights.

Both barrels fire simultaneously

*16 rounds in under 3 seconds

The AF-2011 can be handled by any shooter able to shoot a standard .45 ACP.

It is not only very pleasing to shoot, but very accurate and great fun.

The only gun in the world where brass flies in two different directions.

The AF2011 has amazing target performance for the shooter.

It will group all 18 rounds in a target the size of an orange at 15 yards and a watermelon at 25. The stopping power of the AF2011 is tremendous.

The AF2011 fires 2 bullets simultaneously for a total weight of 460 grains impacting at 1 to 2 inches apart (depending on the distance of the target.)

All 18 rounds, a payload exceeding 4140 grains, can be delivered to the target in about 3 seconds.

The AF2011 features a number of very special parts, such as the single slide, the single frame, the single spur double hammer, the single grip safety, the single body double mainspring housing, the single double cavity magazine floor plate, the long and double magazine latch, the special barrel bushings, the hold open lever and the side lever safety with long shafts.

Most internal parts come as standard 1911 parts.

title: For Sale:  50 BMG Ammo APIT & API
location: Off the Mt Rose Hwy, Reno, Nevada
postcontent:
These are non-corrosive, boxer primed reloads that I bought to shoot through my Browning M2HB Machinegun but I'm selling it too.  I have both APIT & API (armor piercing incendiary tracer).  These were demilled and reconstructed by TNW and they did a fairly sloppy job.  Some of the rounds wobble when rolled on a table as the bullet may not be centered properly. Though clean and sure-fire, I wouldn't use them in a single shot or semiauto rifle.  They run great in a machinegun (looser chamber tolerances) and are labeled "for machinegun use only".

I think for now, I'd like to sell these for pickup here in Reno as I don't know how other states restrict API/APIT ammo.  I know they're a felony in California.  In Nevada, it is unlawful to shoot tracer or incendiary ammo over vegetation, so they suggest the Black Rock Desert as the closest place to shoot near Reno.  You may want to avoid the Burning Man festival out there every Summer unless you have permission.  Due to the extreme fire danger, you must impress me that you have a responsible use for these or I'll refuse the sale.

The rounds are loose packed, 100 rounds in each ammo can at $179 per can.  I'm open to bulk discounts...

title: For Sale:  Vector V51P 7.62x51 HK clone
postcontent:
Full disclosure. I've had this gun for over a year, and it has never worked right for me. My local gunsmith has tinkered with it constantly. Between him troubleshooting, and me test firing and providing feedback, we never could figure it out.  The most recent tests yielded less than one failure per mag of 20rds. So, she's at 95%. I expect that's as good as it's going to get in his hands, and i am not paying him to do any more work with it.  As you can see in the images, the rollers would attempt to protrude and lock, when the bolt is on its recoil path. This caused several dimples along the length of the rails. As with a lot of Vector guns, the receiver pressing is not in spec. The rails are not squared, as they should be. I don't believe this to be the sole issue, as I have seen Vectors with the same incorrect pressings have no problems. So, if you fancy yourself a Vector/HK expert, you may be able to resurrect this guy.

It's got a FAB Defense rail on it. The original handguard will be included. The front sling attachment loop had to be removed, for the FAB rail to fit.

The trigger housing is a PTR unit. The trigger pack is the same one i received with the V51, when i purchased it.

The rubber on the charging handle is tearing slightly. Other than that, the overall finish on the gun is good.

I had this gun as an SBR. It has since been removed from the registry, and is a pistol.

I have a G3 collapsible stock for it, if you wish to make an SBR out of it. The stock is missing a snap ring, which will need to be replaced for proper function. I would recommend a solid stock, actually. Collapsible stock = PAIN.

Well, here's hoping someone can provide a good home. Asking $1,000.00 for the gun. $1,150.00 if you want the stock too.

title: For Sale:  Yugo 59/66 SKS
postcontent:
This is a new commercially manufactured Yugo 59/66 A1 SKS that was made in Yugoslavia by Zastava Arms & imported by InterOrdance (I.O.) in 2003.  Pretty much a collector's item because of it's rarity.  Still new & unfired since it left the factory.  Have 2 - only one is shown in photos.  Both the same except for serial #'s.
Gray web sling, brass oiler with leather pouch, & leather ammo pouch as shown. The cleaning kits are in the stocks.  In the plain cardboard boxes in which they were shipped to me, the original owner, 12 years ago.  Price is firm at this point.
They will be at this weekend's Smoky Mtn Gun Collectors show unless sold before then.  Can provide additional info &/or cell phone # via email to interested persons. 

This I copied off the internet - your search may turn up more info:
“There are about 250 truly un-issued/new M59/66A1's that made it to our shores and survived.  About 500 of these new manufacture M59/66A1's came in with a shipment imported by I/O.  Workers at I/O have informed me about half were sold before the fed's realized they were not surplus military. The half that was unsold was cut up and sold to Numrich as parts. The half sold was grandfathered but technically are not C&R as surplus M59/66A1's are.
These "new" Yugo's can be recognized in the following ways. 
Only the receiver and stock have a serial number.  All other parts are un-numbered. 
The serial will look like 10001A through 10600A stamped in large numbers and letter. 
They never had a bit of cosmo on them.”

postcontent:
This is what I know about the gun. Its an original 1943 Remington-Rand M 1911 A1 US Army Issue. (Only a few blood spots) According to the serial number this gun was shipped in April of 1943. It is stamped with "FJA" inspector's mark. FJA are the initials of Frank J. Atwood, inspector of ordnance. The "P" proof mark is located near the magazine release and on top of the slide, in front of the rear sight. Cross cannons ordnance mark on the right rear of the frame, to the right of the hammer pin. "UNITED STATES PROPERTY" over the serial number with "M1911A1 U.S. ARMY" to the right of the slide stop pin. Also has the G marking on top of the frame next to the disconnector and P proof mark on top of the slide, in front of the rear sight. HS marked barrel. HS is the marking of High Standard.

This gun is all original, and a wartime piece, as you can tell by the blood spots on the slide and grip. It also comes with original U.S. marked Military issued Holster. This gun still functions perfect, and feeds regular hard ball ammo without fail. A great collector piece for any WWII collection. 1250$ cash firm.. title: For Sale:  1942 Colt M1911 A1 National Match
postcontent:
RARE 1942 Colt M1911 A1 national match pistol. This is what I know about the gun. Its an original 1942 Colt M 1911 A1 US Army Issue. (matching numbers except slide does not show serial number behind hammer) According to the serial number this gun was shipped in May of 1942. It is stamped with WB inside a Box for Colonel Waldemar S. Broberg, Hartford/Springfield Ordnance District, Army Inspector of Ordnance: July 1, 1941 - June 16, 1942. The WB inspected pistols are a little more rare for that time frame.

Not sure how this gun made it back to the states, but it appears the gun was made into a national match pistol during the 1950's or early 1960's, it does not have "NM" stamped on the slide.. But not all pistols back then were stamped with "NM" for national match. There are two types of Camp Perry National Match pistols.. The kind sent back to Armories and stamped SA for Springfield Armory and NM for Colt Armory. These were tuned, and fitted by the armory for military camp perry match shooting. The second was private gunsmiths these were done in competition with the armories for the same reason. Many prominent Gunsmiths of the time wanted national match recognition and made their own finally tuned pistols. It appears this one might have been done by the military, as the barrel has been re-stamped. This gun is in its original time frame finish (parkerized). All Proof markings to fit era. Bore is excellent and looks shinning.

This pistol is a shooter. It is amazingly tight and special fitted for accuracy. Its an amazing piece of history and looks beautiful as well. Definitely a one of a kind 1911. Would be a prize piece for any collection.

1250$ cash firm.. Thats a fair price, they are going for more than that.. I have many pictures if you want more. FTF in tulsa area only.. email or text 918-four02-zero854.

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P6 (P225)
postcontent:
I have for sale a Sig Sauer P6 (P225).  It was made in West Germany in the early 1980's.  It is in very nice shape and would make a wonderful concealed carry piece, as it is a single stack    magazine.  The pistol comes with the box and papers (in German), and 1 magazine.

From wikipedia:
The only difference between the P6 and P225—the P225 (which was adopted by US civilian law enforcement) has a lighter trigger pull, whereas the P6's trigger pull is heavier. The P225 has tritium fixed sights; P6s had fixed sights only. Genuine P225s manufactured for the West German Police will have a "P6" stamp on the right side of the slide. A new police standard was adopted in Germany in 1995, and the P225 is in the process of being replaced. German police pistols can be identified by the hammer, which has small "ear" or "hook". According to section 7.7 of the German manual, the cutout is the Deformationssporn, which means “deformation spur”. This was a requirement of the West German Police for all their P6 pistols, to alert police armorers if the pistol was dropped on its hammer. Many of these surplus German police pistols have been imported into the U.S. recently. Because of its compact size, the P225/P6 is quite readily usable for concealed carry. In U.S. states where standard capacity magazines were prohibited, the P6/P225 was usually in high demand.
